CSS Variables (Custom Properties)

CSS variables, also known as custom properties, allow you to define reusable values that can be used throughout your stylesheet. This helps you maintain consistency and make changes more efficiently. Â  

How to Define and Use CSS Variables:

Define the Variable:
You define a variable using the -- syntax. For example:
:root {
    --primary-color: #336699;
    --secondary-color: #f2f2f2;
    --font-size: 16px;
}
2.Use the Variable:
To use a variable, you reference it using the var() function. For example:

CSS
body {
    background-color: var(--secondary-color);
    font-size: var(--font-size);
}

h1 {
    color: var(--primary-color);
}
Example: Changing Variable Values
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Variables Example</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph.</p>
</body>
</html>

CSS
:root {
    --primary-color: #336699;
    --secondary-color: #f2f2f2;
    --font-size: 16px;
}

body {
    background-color: var(--secondary-color);
    font-size: var(--font-size);
}

h1 {
    color: var(--primary-color);
    font-size: 2em;
}

/* To change the primary color: */
:root {
    --primary-color: red;
}
